Advertising[edit]




W.B. Mason Logo






A W.B. Mason Blizzard copy paper box is featured on the poster for the 2014 Academy Award recipient Spotlight.


In 1986 the company introduced its iconic slogan, "Who But W.B. Mason". Later, the slogan was combined with a portrait from the 1890s of founder William Betts Mason to synthesize their current corporate logo. The logo features two U.S. flags flanking the portrait of W.B. Mason. The flag on the right has 50 stars to represent the current state of the union, but the one on the left shows only 45 stars, the configuration at the time of the company's founding in 1898. In 1997 W.B. Mason began advertising on television. Its inaugural commercial was played during the 1997 Super Bowl. Besides their commercials, their fully decorated trucks and baseball park signage serve as W.B. Mason's primary forms of advertising. Both their trucks and baseball park sinage have become an iconic part of their brand and have been spotted in many movies and on local network television.



Movies With W.B. Mason Advertisements


W.B. Mason Truck
Elf, RIPD, In Her Shoes, In Good Company, Sharknado 2, Whitey: United States of America v. James J. Bulger,


W.B. Mason Baseball Stadium Sign
Ted, Minority Report, Fever Pitch, Adjustment Bureau, Moneyball, PS I Love You


W.B. Mason Brand Paper Box
Spotlight, Edge of Darkness, Definitely, Maybe







Truck fleet: tractor trailer, furniture truck, same-day delivery truck, and supply truck



Sponsorships[edit]
Baseball[edit]
W.B. Mason is the "Official Office Products Supplier" to the Boston Red Sox, Philadelphia Phillies, New York Yankees, New York Mets, Pittsburgh Pirates, Washington Nationals, Cleveland Indians, and Tampa Bay Rays. W.B. Mason has its corporate logo displayed throughout all eight team's home ballparks: Fenway Park in Boston, Citizens Bank Park in Philadelphia, Yankee Stadium and Citi Field in New York, PNC Park in Pittsburgh, Progressive Field in Cleveland, and Nationals Park in Washington. In 2003 W.B. Mason placed its first ball park advertisement on the Green Monster at Fenway Park; this was the first advertisement painted on the Green Monster since 1947. [15]

